The staff accommodated our Chicago style pizza order at the very end of their workday. The price was reasonably good for that much food - the crust is really thick and huge! However, this wasn't real Chicago style pizza (rich and decadent deep dish). It was simply big-crust pizza, which is very filling for the price. The crust is prebaked and taken out of the fridge for assembly. The place also offers NY style by the slice, garlic knots, etc. Pretty standard. Service is reasonably fast.

I only found this place recently because its hidden in a narrow side street, but I'm glad I know it exists now!  One of the best things about the pizza is that it has a puffy crust while still having char on the underside. Seems very rare to find a crust like this in this city. It was also very cheesy and the sauce tasted good. The main problem that I had with the pizza was that it was extremely greasy. Because of how greasy and heavy it was, I had some trouble finishing my second slice. As for pricing, one regular slice was $3.25, so it's 25 cents more than what you would typically find in Manhattan.  I saw the sign saying they had cannolis, so naturally I had to try that as well. It tasted amazing. Was pretty expensive though (also $3.25). (Side note: the cannoli looks messed up in the pic I attached because it was in my backpack for 3 hours before I ate it. It prob won't look like that when you get it.)  It has a decent amount of seating and is right next to the park. Definitely recommend this place.

Stopped by for the first time today: great pizza (meat lover's and white were both fantastic), great custom soda (root beer; I'll try the black cherry next time). Quick service, not very busy; also, not much table space, so plan on taking it to go. Highly recommended for lunch or a quick bite.  Oh yeah: Also, I love the ballsiness of Chicago-style pizza in NYC. GET OUTTA HEYA. Also, when I asked the guy behind the counter what his favorite slice was, he answered, "I dunno. I eat beans and rice." Classic.
